# ROVEXO Account Architecture (Single Source of Truth)

ROVEXO has **one unified user account**. There are no separate Buyer or Seller
accounts. Role is derived from the **action**, not the account:

- Buy an item → acts as Buyer
- Publish a listing → acts as Seller
- The same account does both, interchangeably. Buyer = Seller = Buyer.

## Account types
Exactly two, and **both can buy and sell**:
1. **Personal Account**
2. **Verified Business Account** (can buy, sell, receive payments, manage orders)

There is no "buy-only" / "sell-only" account. Any user may request Business
status; it is granted only after ROVEXO verification, and the account keeps the
**same unified identity** while gaining Business features.

## UI / UX rules (mandatory)
- ❌ Never create, imply, or require separate Buyer and Seller accounts.
- ❌ Never require "switching accounts" or creating another account to sell.
- ❌ Never duplicate profile data across roles.
- ✅ Always one unified account; features appear by permission/action.
- ✅ Navigation, dashboards, menus, permissions, and settings must reflect the
  unified model. Avoid wording/workflows implying Buyer and Seller are different
  account types.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — implies separate accounts / account switching
<Link href="/seller/signup">Create a seller account</Link>
<Button onClick={switchToSellerAccount}>Switch to selling account</Button>

// ✅ GOOD — same account, action-based capability
<Link href="/sell">Start selling</Link>
<Button onClick={requestBusinessVerification}>Get verified as a business</Button>
```

Buyer/seller **dashboards or views** are fine as action-oriented surfaces of the
one account (e.g. "Selling" and "Buying" areas) — just never as separate logins,
identities, or profiles.

## Legal
ROVEXO is a marketplace platform. Each seller/business is responsible for their
own legal, tax, accounting, licensing, and reporting obligations. The platform
does not replace those responsibilities.
